In a #small pot{}, combine @Jasmine Rice{3/4%cup}, 1¼ cups water, and a big
pinch of @salt{pinch}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer.
Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, wash and dry produce.

Trim and thinly slice @Scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Trim and
peel @Carrots{6%ounce}. Using a #peeler{}, shave carrots lengthwise into ribbons,
rotating as you go, until you get to the core; discard core. Trim and halve
@Zucchini{1%unit} lengthwise; thinly slice crosswise into half-moons. Peel and
mince @Ginger{1%thumb} and @Garlic{1%clove}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine scallion whites, @White Wine Vinegar{5%teaspoon},
and a pinch of salt. Set aside to pickle, stirring occasionally, until ready
to serve.

In a separate small bowl, combine @Sesame Oil{1%tablespoon}, @Gochujang Sauce{1/2%ounce},
half the @Soy Sauce{2%tablespoon} (you'll use the rest later), and
@Sugar{1%tablespoon}. Stir until sugar has dissolved.

> Use 2 TBSP sugar for 4 servings.

Heat a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{1%tablespoon} in a large, preferably
nonstick, pan over medium-high heat. Add carrots; season with @salt{} and
@Pepper{}. Cook, stirring, until slightly softened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Remove
from pan and set aside.

Add another drizzle of oil to pan. Add zucchini; season with salt and pepper.
Cook until browned and tender, ~{3-5%minutes} per side. Remove from pan and
set aside with carrots.

Heat a drizzle of oil in same pan over medium-high heat. Add @Ground Turkey{10%ounce},
ginger, and garlic. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until turkey is browned
and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Add remaining soy sauce and cook, stirring, until liquid has mostly evaporated,
~{1-2%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

> Ground Turkey is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.

Fluff rice with a #fork{} and season with salt and pepper; divide between
#bowls{}.

Arrange turkey and veggies over rice. Top with pickled scallion whites (and
pickling liquid). Drizzle with sauce. Sprinkle with scallion greens and serve.

> This dish takes its name from the Korean word for mixing rice. Which is exactly
what you're meant to do after serving it: Put your rice in a bowl, add the toppings,
and mix it all together so that those flavors and textures combine in a glorious
mishmash. There are plenty of flavors and textures going on here, too, like
sweet carrot, tender zucchini, and pork tossed with garlic, ginger, and soy sauce.